    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Bias in LLMs Is Different"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Bias in a traditional classification model is typically defined relative to a measurable ground truth: the model's error rate differs across demographic groups. LLMs introduce three additional complications. First, many outputs are "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "open-ended",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 there is no single correct answer, so \"bias\" must be defined in terms of quality, sentiment, or toxicity differentials rather than error rates. Second, LLMs are pre-trained on web-scale text that "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "contains and amplifies",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the biases of the societies that produced it. Third, LLMs surface bias "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "contextually",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 the same model may perform equitably on a benchmark but produce stereotyped outputs when given prompts involving names, dialects, or topic framing. Fixing LLM bias requires understanding exactly where it enters the pipeline:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Four bias types (Pre-existing, Measurement, Representation, Aggregation/Emergent) mapped to their pipeline stage and detection/mitigation approach"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pre-existing Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pre-existing bias originates in the world before any data is collected. It is the systematic inequity embedded in the text that humans have historically written. Web crawls, books, and social-media corpora all reflect who had access to publishing, what topics were covered, and how groups were described in the language of their era. The model learns statistical associations from this text, so it inherits the stereotypes present in it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Word Embedding Association Test (WEAT) measures pre-existing bias in embedding spaces by comparing cosine similarities between target words (e.g. occupations) and attribute words (e.g. gender terms). A high WEAT effect size indicates the model associates occupations with one gender more than the other:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom typing import Callable\n\n# WEAT effect size \u2014 Caliskan et al., 2017\n# All vectors must be L2-normalised before calling this function.\n\ndef cosine(a: np.ndarray, b: np.ndarray) -> float:\n    return float(np.dot(a, b))  # assumes pre-normalised\n\ndef association(\n    word: np.ndarray,\n    attribute_a: list[np.ndarray],\n    attribute_b: list[np.ndarray],\n) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Mean cosine similarity to group A minus mean to group B.\"\"\"\n    mean_a = np.mean([cosine(word, a) for a in attribute_a])\n    mean_b = np.mean([cosine(word, b) for b in attribute_b])\n    return float(mean_a - mean_b)\n\ndef weat_effect_size(\n    target_x: list[np.ndarray],     # e.g. career words\n    target_y: list[np.ndarray],     # e.g. family words\n    attribute_a: list[np.ndarray],  # e.g. male names\n    attribute_b: list[np.ndarray],  # e.g. female names\n) -> float:\n    \"\"\"\n    Cohen's d analogue for WEAT.\n    Positive \u2192 target_x more strongly associated with attribute_a.\n    |d| > 0.8 is considered a large effect (biased).\n    \"\"\"\n    assocs_x = [association(w, attribute_a, attribute_b) for w in target_x]\n    assocs_y = [association(w, attribute_a, attribute_b) for w in target_y]\n    all_assocs = assocs_x + assocs_y\n    numerator = np.mean(assocs_x) - np.mean(assocs_y)\n    denominator = np.std(all_assocs, ddof=0)\n    return float(numerator / denominator) if denominator != 0 else 0.0\n\n# Example usage (embeddings must be pre-computed):\n# d = weat_effect_size(career_vecs, family_vecs, male_name_vecs, female_name_vecs)\n# if abs(d) > 0.8:\n#     print(f\"Large gender\u2013career association: d={d:.2f}\")\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measurement Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measurement bias arises when the feature used to represent a concept is an imperfect or discriminatory proxy. In LLM pipelines, measurement bias appears in two forms:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Proxy features in training.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " A model fine-tuned on customer-service tickets that includes zip code as a feature learns a proxy for race and income. Outputs then implicitly discriminate even if no protected attribute was used explicitly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Annotator label bias.",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Human raters bring their own cultural framing to labelling tasks. If annotators are demographically homogeneous, the labels encode that demographic's perspective. Systematically lower quality labels for text in African-American Vernacular English (AAVE), for example, train the model to rate that dialect as lower quality."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inter-annotator agreement measures whether labels are reliable. Low Fleiss' kappa (\u03ba) signals that labels are subjective or contested \u2014 exactly the condition where annotator demographics become a confounding factor:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from itertools import combinations\n\ndef fleiss_kappa(ratings: list[list[int]], n_categories: int) -> float:\n    \"\"\"\n    Compute Fleiss' kappa for n raters \u00d7 m items.\n    ratings: outer list = items, inner list = category assigned by each rater.\n    n_categories: total number of distinct label categories.\n    Returns kappa in [-1, 1]; > 0.6 is considered substantial agreement.\n    \"\"\"\n    n_items = len(ratings)\n    n_raters = len(ratings[0])\n\n    # Per-item proportion of raters assigning each category\n    item_counts = [\n        [row.count(k) for k in range(n_categories)]\n        for row in ratings\n    ]\n\n    # Overall proportion for each category\n    total_ratings = n_items * n_raters\n    p_k = [\n        sum(item_counts[i][k] for i in range(n_items)) / total_ratings\n        for k in range(n_categories)\n    ]\n\n    # Mean proportion of agreeing pairs per item\n    P_i = [\n        (sum(c * (c - 1) for c in item_counts[i]) / (n_raters * (n_raters - 1)))\n        for i in range(n_items)\n    ]\n    P_bar = sum(P_i) / n_items\n\n    # Expected agreement by chance\n    P_e = sum(p ** 2 for p in p_k)\n\n    if P_e == 1.0:\n        return 1.0\n    return (P_bar - P_e) / (1.0 - P_e)\n\n\n# Example: 3 annotators labelling 5 sentences as safe(0) or toxic(1)\nratings_example = [\n    [0, 0, 0],  # all agree: safe\n    [0, 0, 1],  # disagreement\n    [1, 1, 0],  # disagreement\n    [1, 1, 1],  # all agree: toxic\n    [0, 1, 0],  # disagreement\n]\nkappa = fleiss_kappa(ratings_example, n_categories=2)\nprint(f\"Fleiss kappa: {kappa:.3f}\")   # \u2192 0.308 (fair agreement \u2014 too low for safety labels)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Representation Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Representation bias occurs when some groups are systematically under-represented in the training corpus or fine-tuning dataset. An under-represented group receives less gradient signal during training, so the model's performance on that group lags behind its overall average. In LLMs this shows up as poorer language quality, higher refusal rates, or lower semantic coherence for text in under-represented dialects, languages, or about under-represented topics."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import Counter\n\ndef detect_representation_gaps(\n    texts: list[str],\n    group_labels: list[str],\n    min_fraction: float = 0.05,\n) -> dict[str, dict]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Report groups whose fraction of the dataset is below min_fraction.\n    texts: the actual text samples.\n    group_labels: parallel list assigning each text to a demographic group.\n    Returns a dict of {group: {\"count\": N, \"fraction\": f, \"gap\": bool}}.\n    \"\"\"\n    total = len(texts)\n    counts = Counter(group_labels)\n    result = {}\n    for group, count in sorted(counts.items()):\n        fraction = count / total\n        result[group] = {\n            \"count\": count,\n            \"fraction\": round(fraction, 4),\n            \"gap\": fraction < min_fraction,\n        }\n    return result\n\n# Example\nlabels = [\"en-US\"] * 8000 + [\"en-GB\"] * 1000 + [\"en-IN\"] * 200 + [\"en-NG\"] * 80\nreport = detect_representation_gaps(texts=[\"...\"] * len(labels), group_labels=labels)\nfor group, stats in report.items():\n    flag = \"\u26a0\ufe0f  UNDER-REPRESENTED\" if stats[\"gap\"] else \"ok\"\n    print(f\"  {group}: {stats['fraction']:.1%}  {flag}\")\n# en-US: 86.4%  ok\n# en-GB: 10.8%  ok\n# en-IN:  2.2%  \u26a0\ufe0f  UNDER-REPRESENTED\n# en-NG:  0.9%  \u26a0\ufe0f  UNDER-REPRESENTED\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Aggregation and Emergent Bias"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Aggregation bias arises when a single model is trained to serve heterogeneous subgroups whose optimal decision boundaries differ. Averaging across groups during training means the model fits the majority group well and the minority group poorly. This is distinct from representation bias: even a perfectly balanced dataset can produce aggregation bias if the underlying task relationship is different for different subgroups."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Emergent bias is a deployment-phase phenomenon: the model's outputs shape future training data or user behaviour, which feeds back into the next version of the model, amplifying the original skew. A hiring-assistance LLM that rates resumes from one demographic slightly lower will, if used to filter candidates, produce a workforce that then produces less training data from that demographic, making the next model worse:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\ndef simulate_feedback_loop(\n    initial_representation: float,  # e.g. 0.15 for 15% group A in initial pool\n    selection_bias: float,           # how much less likely group A is to be selected (0.0\u20131.0)\n    rounds: int = 5,\n) -> list[float]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Simulate how representation of a minority group evolves over successive\n    model training \u2192 deployment \u2192 data-collection cycles.\n    selection_bias=0.10 means group A is 10 % less likely to be selected per round.\n    \"\"\"\n    rep = initial_representation\n    history = [rep]\n    for _ in range(rounds):\n        # Group A selection rate is reduced by selection_bias relative to group B\n        selected_a = rep * (1.0 - selection_bias)\n        selected_b = (1.0 - rep)\n        total = selected_a + selected_b\n        rep = selected_a / total if total > 0 else 0\n        history.append(round(rep, 4))\n    return history\n\ntrajectory = simulate_feedback_loop(\n    initial_representation=0.20,\n    selection_bias=0.10,\n    rounds=6,\n)\nprint(\"Group A representation over rounds:\", trajectory)\n# [0.2, 0.1818, 0.1667, 0.1538, 0.1429, 0.1333, 0.125]\n# A 10 % selection bias shrinks minority representation by a third in 6 cycles.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Disparate Impact Analysis"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Disparate impact testing compares the selection or acceptance rates between demographic groups. A ratio below 0.8 (the \"four-fifths rule\" from US employment law) flags statistically significant adverse impact. The same principle applies to LLM outputs: compare quality scores, refusal rates, or sentiment across groups:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass DisparateImpactResult:\n    reference_group: str\n    comparison_group: str\n    reference_rate: float\n    comparison_rate: float\n    ratio: float              # comparison_rate / reference_rate\n    adverse_impact: bool      # True if ratio < 0.80\n\ndef disparate_impact(\n    outcomes: dict[str, list[bool]],   # group -> [True=positive, False=negative]\n    reference_group: str | None = None,\n) -> list[DisparateImpactResult]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Compute pairwise disparate impact ratios.\n    If reference_group is None, the group with the highest positive rate is used.\n    \"\"\"\n    rates = {g: sum(v) / len(v) for g, v in outcomes.items() if v}\n\n    if reference_group is None:\n        reference_group = max(rates, key=lambda g: rates[g])\n\n    ref_rate = rates[reference_group]\n    results = []\n    for group, rate in rates.items():\n        if group == reference_group:\n            continue\n        ratio = rate / ref_rate if ref_rate > 0 else 0.0\n        results.append(DisparateImpactResult(\n            reference_group=reference_group,\n            comparison_group=group,\n            reference_rate=round(ref_rate, 4),\n            comparison_rate=round(rate, 4),\n            ratio=round(ratio, 4),\n            adverse_impact=ratio < 0.80,\n        ))\n    return results\n\n# Example: LLM r\u00e9sum\u00e9 scoring \u2014 fraction of r\u00e9sum\u00e9s rated \"strong\"\noutcomes = {\n    \"group_majority\":  [True] * 70 + [False] * 30,  # 70 % positive rate\n    \"group_minority_A\": [True] * 50 + [False] * 50, # 50 % positive rate\n    \"group_minority_B\": [True] * 40 + [False] * 60, # 40 % positive rate\n}\nfor r in disparate_impact(outcomes):\n    flag = \"ADVERSE IMPACT\" if r.adverse_impact else \"ok\"\n    print(f\"  {r.comparison_group} vs {r.reference_group}: ratio={r.ratio:.2f}  {flag}\")\n# group_minority_A vs group_majority: ratio=0.71  ADVERSE IMPACT\n# group_minority_B vs group_majority: ratio=0.57  ADVERSE IMPACT\n"
          }
        ]
      },
